06698nam a22011895i 9781487528225DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20212021onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875282257 a10.3138/97814875282252doi  a(DE-B1597)583316  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aD744.7.E8 7aHIS0271002bisacsh04a940.53/122300aAuthenticity and Victimhood after the Second World War :bNarratives from Europe and East Asia /ced. by Daqing Yang, Herrn Prof. Dr. Andreas Wirsching, Randall Hansen, Achim Saupe. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b1 B&W illustration, 1 figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGerman and European Studies0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe shadow of the Second World War was filled with many terrible crimes, such as genocide, forced migration and labour, human-made famine, forced sterilizations, and dispossession. None of these atrocities were new, but they all occurred on an unprecedented scale. Authenticity and Victimhood after the Second World War examines victim groups constructed in the twentieth century in the aftermath of these experiences. The collection explores the concept of authenticity through an examination of victims’ histories and the construction of victimhood in Europe and East Asia. Chapters consider how notions of historical authenticity influence the self-identification and public recognition of a given social group, the tensions arising from individual and group experiences of victimhood, and the resulting, sometimes divergent, interpretation of historical events. Drawing from case studies on topics including the Holocaust, the siege of Leningrad, American air raids on Japan, and forced migrations from Eastern Europe, Authenticity and Victimhood after the Second World War shows the trends towards a victim-centred collective memory and the role trends play in memory politics and public commemorative culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCollective memoryzEast Asia. 0aCollective memoryzEurope. 0aWar victimszEast Asia. 0aWar victimszEurope. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xAtrocitiesxHistoriography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zEast AsiaxHistoriography. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zEuropexHistoriography. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War II.2bisacsh  aChina.  aEast Asia.  aEurope.  aHitler.  aHolocaust.  aJapanmassacre.  aNazi Germany.  aSecond World War.  aShoah.  aWWII.  aauthenticity.  acivilian casualties.  afamine.  aforced migration.  agenocide.  apostwar commemoration.  avictimhood.1 aBeer, Mathias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristophe, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlorin, Moritz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen, Randall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen, Randall, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHof, Tobias, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoose, Ingo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOrr, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSatoshi, Nakano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaupe, Achim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSaupe, Achim, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchwartz, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVoronina, Tatiana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWirsching, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4